k, and reflect on how architecture can respond to todays material and environmental urgencies, with clay at the centre.___Tickets are free with a donation to our local charity partners Made In Hackney.	Clay | Culture | Carbon: 'Meet The Makers'	Dive into the 'Clay | Culture | Carbon' exhibition during a special after-hours event, offering a unique opportunity to connect directly with the talented makers, key collaborators, and insightful curators behind this innovative showcase on 10 July 2025.	Dive into the 'Clay | Culture | Carbon' exhibition during a special after-hours event, offering a unique opportunity to connect directly with the talented makers, key collaborators, and insightful curators behind this innovative showcase.	Join us for an exclusive 'Studio Late' to immerse yourself in the 'Clay | Culture | Carbon' exhibition beyond regular hours. This unique event provides a direct conduit to the creative minds and research driving the exhibition's core themes: clay as a pivotal medium for carbon, culture, and collaborative practices. You'll gain firsthand insights into how materials are transformed, from site-sourced earth to reimagined bricks, exploring concepts of regenerative making and found materials.\n\nThe evening will feature engaging conversations with exhibition curator Elly Ward Morris, who will delve into the show's craft-focused, research-led, and community-rooted ethos. Discover 'co-making' principles with David Storring, Head of Sustainability, and Edie Parfitt from CELLA, the collective behind the central installation. Learn about groundbreaking alternatives to carbon-intensive fired-clay brick production, including earth bricks from Arup's Laura Marcheggiano and 'Circulabrick' by Dave Mills of Lyons & Annoot. Conclude by exploring the experimental clay bodies and innovative firing techniques of 'Hackney Potter' Adele Williams, who forages raw clay for her practice.\n\nThis event offers a significant opportunity to understand how architecture c