ork, stone, brick or timber, CSK are keen to explore the benefits of material reuse and how this can be utilised to create an architectural language specific to site and place.AccessibilityThames Lido is a short walk from Reading Station, with parking available at Hills Meadow Car Park. A dedicated disabled space is available at the venue, and blue badge holders may park on the double yellow lines on Kings Meadow Road for up to two hours.The Lidos reception is fully wheelchair accessible, and a lift near the bar entrance provides access to the first-floor function room.	RIBA Berkshire Sustainability talks 2025: Between living time and rocky space	Join RIBA Berkshire for an evening lecture with Matthew Barnett Howland and Dido Milne, exploring material life cycles and architectures connection to nature. The event takes place on 21 October 2025.	Join RIBA Berkshire for an evening lecture with Matthew Barnett Howland and Dido Milne, exploring material life cycles and architectures connection to nature.	Delve into the critical conversation around sustainable architecture and material life cycles at the RIBA Berkshire Sustainability talks 2025. This illuminating evening features acclaimed architects Matthew Barnett Howland and Dido Milne from CSK Architects, known for their groundbreaking work, including the RIBA Stirling Prize-shortlisted Cork House. They will challenge conventional perceptions of buildings as permanent structures, instead presenting them as dynamic processes intertwined with natural systems. Through compelling case studies and original diagrams, the speakers will explore the intricate relationship between earth systems, building components, and architectural design, highlighting the profound impact of material choices on our environment. Attendees will gain valuable insights into material reuse, renewable resources, and innovative approaches to creating site-specific architectural languages. The event also provides a unique opportunity to network with 