2309	https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/joy-diversion-popular-modernism-in-manchester-tickets-1700089386119?aff=ebdssbdestsearch	event-bright	Title: Joy Diversion: Popular Modernism in Manchester\\nShort Description: Professor Justin OConnor, Adelaide University, and Hallsworth Visiting Professor, University of Manchester\\nLocation: University Place, Theatre A, University of Manchester 176 Oxford Road Manchester M13 9PL United Kingdom\\nCost: Free\\nDates: Wednesday, October 29  5 - 6:30pm GMT\\nDescription: Research Seminar - Department of Art History and Cultural Practices, University of ManchesterJoy Diversion: Popular Modernism in ManchesterJustin OConnor, Professor of Cultural Economy, Adelaide University, Visiting Professor, Shanghai Jiaotong University, and Hallsworth Visiting Professor, University of ManchesterAbstractThis lecture takes a retrospective view of Manchesters creative city narrative and the band Joy Divisions role within it. The focus will be less on the winners and losers of the citys subsequent wave of property-led gentrification, and more on the specific moment in which Joy Division emerged in the late 1970s. Manchesters regeneration narrative mobilised Manchesters music scene, and Joy Division were emblematic of the citys post-industrial reinvention. In part this reinvention concerns popular modernism, the encounter of popular culture with modernist currents in art and architecture, which for Mark Fisher testified to a future still open to possibility. Manchester: Original Modern comes directly out of this. Yet much of Joy Division music was about No Future, or as Tony Wilson had it, in relation to the transition from punk and post-punk: from fuck off to were fucked. How is it that this bleak music became anthemic to the re-invented Manchester? Might the moment of Joy Division connote the ending of something, a musical time-image in which a certain past could be mourned as it slipped away? Was it as much about thwarted possibilities than a preparation for the regeneration to come? In this sense maybe Joy Division speak more to our moment now, more than the narratives of boosterism in which they have become embalmed.BiographyJustin OConnor is Professor of Cultural Economy at Adelaide University, Visiting Professor at the School of Cultural Management, Shanghai Jiaotong University, and Hallsworth Visiting Professor at the University of Manchester. Justins research led to the establishment of Manchesters Creative Industries Development Service (CIDS), of which he was co-chair. Justin was lead academic advisor to Manchesters Urbis museum of the contemporary city, and led the team which established Manchesters Northern Quarter. Between 2012-18 he was a member of the UNESCO Expert Facility, supporting the 2005 Convention on the Protection and Promotion of Cultural Diversity.Justin recently co-authored Red Creative: Culture and Modernity in China (2020, Intellect), and published his latest monograph Culture is Not an Industry (2024,) with Manchester University Press as part of the Manchester Capitalism series. More information at https://justin-oconnor.com [justin-oconnor.com]	Joy Diversion: Popular Modernism in Manchester	This research seminar delves into Manchester's "creative city" narrative, exploring the iconic band Joy Division's impact and the concept of "popular modernism" in shaping the city's regeneration on 29 October 2025.	This research seminar delves into Manchester's "creative city" narrative, exploring the iconic band Joy Division's impact and the concept of "popular modernism" in shaping the city's regeneration.	Professor Justin OConnor presents a compelling research seminar, "Joy Diversion: Popular Modernism in Manchester," offering a retrospective on Manchester's "creative city" evolution through the lens of the iconic band Joy Division. This engaging discussion moves beyond typical gentrification narratives to examine the specific cultural moment of the late 1970s when Joy Division emerged, shaping Manchesters post-industrial reinvention. Professor O'Connor explores "popular modernism," the unique fusion of popular culture with modernist currents in art and architecture, a concept integral to the "Manchester: Original Modern" ethos. The seminar will unravel the paradox of how Joy Division's famously bleak "No Future" music became anthemic to the citys vibrant reinvention, questioning if their sound reflected thwarted possibilities rather than a prelude to future regeneration. This insightful analysis considers how Joy Division might speak more profoundly to contemporary urban dynamics than to the boosterism narratives often associated with them. Attendees will gain a deeper understanding of cultural economy, urban planning, and the complex interplay between music, architecture, and city identity. This seminar is particularly useful for architects interested in how cultural narratives and popular movements influence urban design, regeneration strategies, and the evolving identity of cities.	29 Oct 2025, 17:0018:30	20251029	University Place, Theatre A, University of Manchester, 176 Oxford Road, Manchester, United Kingdom	Free	t	18283	draft	2025-09-15 13:55:50.788257	2025-09-15 13:24:29.605588	514
